## Q3 — System Calls (File Copy without standard C functions)

### What is being asked?
Copy `source.txt` to `dest.txt` using ONLY system calls — `open()`, `read()`, `write()`, `close()`. No `fopen`, `fread`, `fwrite` allowed. Then verify using `stat()`.

### What are System Calls?
System calls are direct requests to the OS kernel. `fopen()` is a C library wrapper — underneath it also calls `open()`. Here we skip the wrapper and call the OS directly.

---

### FILE: `filecopy.c`

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <fcntl.h>      // open()
#include <unistd.h>     // read(), write(), close()
#include <sys/stat.h>   // stat()

int main() {
    int src_fd, dest_fd;
    char buffer[1024];
    int bytes_read;
    struct stat src_info, dest_info;

    // Step 1: Open source file for reading
    src_fd = open("source.txt", O_RDONLY);
    if (src_fd < 0) {
        printf("Error: Cannot open source.txt\n");
        return 1;
    }
    printf("Source file opened. FD = %d\n", src_fd);

    // Step 2: Create/open destination file for writing
    // O_WRONLY = write only
    // O_CREAT  = create if not exists
    // O_TRUNC  = clear it if it exists
    // 0644     = file permissions (owner can read+write, others can read)
    dest_fd = open("dest.txt", O_WRONLY | O_CREAT | O_TRUNC, 0644);
    if (dest_fd < 0) {
        printf("Error: Cannot create dest.txt\n");
        close(src_fd);
        return 1;
    }
    printf("Destination file created. FD = %d\n", dest_fd);

    // Step 3: Read from source, write to destination in a loop
    // We read 1024 bytes at a time until nothing is left
    while ((bytes_read = read(src_fd, buffer, sizeof(buffer))) > 0) {
        int bytes_written = write(dest_fd, buffer, bytes_read);
        if (bytes_written < 0) {
            printf("Error: Write failed!\n");
            close(src_fd);
            close(dest_fd);
            return 1;
        }
    }

    if (bytes_read < 0) {
        printf("Error: Read failed!\n");
    } else {
        printf("File copy complete!\n");
    }

    // Step 4: Close both files
    close(src_fd);
    close(dest_fd);

    // Step 5: Verify using stat()
    stat("source.txt", &src_info);
    stat("dest.txt", &dest_info);

    printf("Source size  : %ld bytes\n", src_info.st_size);
    printf("Dest size    : %ld bytes\n", dest_info.st_size);

    if (src_info.st_size == dest_info.st_size) {
        printf("Verification: SUCCESS — sizes match!\n");
    } else {
        printf("Verification: FAILED — sizes don't match!\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
```

**Line-by-line explanation:**

| Code | What it does |
|------|-------------|
| `open("source.txt", O_RDONLY)` | Opens file, returns a file descriptor (a number like 3, 4...). If negative → error |
| `open("dest.txt", O_WRONLY\|O_CREAT\|O_TRUNC, 0644)` | Creates dest.txt. `O_CREAT` = make it if missing. `O_TRUNC` = wipe it if exists |
| `read(src_fd, buffer, 1024)` | Reads up to 1024 bytes into buffer. Returns how many bytes were actually read. 0 = EOF |
| `write(dest_fd, buffer, bytes_read)` | Writes exactly `bytes_read` bytes from buffer to dest file |
| `close(src_fd)` | Releases the file descriptor. Always do this |
| `stat("source.txt", &src_info)` | Fills `src_info` with file details. `st_size` = size in bytes |

---

