## Q4 — Multithreading (Array sum with 4 threads)

### What is being asked?
Create an array of 100 integers. Split it into 4 parts of 25. Give each part to a separate thread. Each thread computes its sum. Main program adds all 4 partial sums.

### What is a Thread?
A thread is a lightweight unit of execution inside a process. Think of 4 cashiers at a supermarket — each handles their own queue simultaneously instead of one cashier doing everything.

---

### FILE: `bank_sum.c`

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <pthread.h>

#define TOTAL   100   // Total elements in array
#define THREADS 4     // Number of threads
#define CHUNK   25    // Each thread handles 25 elements

int arr[TOTAL];             // Shared array (filled in main)
long partial_sum[THREADS];  // Each thread writes its result here

// This function runs inside each thread
// 'arg' is the thread's ID (0, 1, 2, or 3)
void* compute_sum(void* arg) {
    int id = *((int*)arg);  // Convert void* to int*

    int start = id * CHUNK;        // Thread 0→0, Thread 1→25, Thread 2→50, Thread 3→75
    int end   = start + CHUNK;     // Thread 0→25, Thread 1→50, etc.

    long sum = 0;
    for (int i = start; i < end; i++) {
        sum += arr[i];
    }

    partial_sum[id] = sum;  // Save result in its own slot — no conflict with other threads

    printf("Thread %d: arr[%d to %d] = %ld\n", id, start, end-1, sum);

    pthread_exit(NULL);  // Thread finishes here
}

int main() {
    pthread_t threads[THREADS];  // OS thread handles
    int ids[THREADS];            // Our custom IDs (0-3)

    // Fill array: arr[0]=1, arr[1]=2, ..., arr[99]=100
    for (int i = 0; i < TOTAL; i++) {
        arr[i] = i + 1;
    }

    // Create 4 threads
    for (int i = 0; i < THREADS; i++) {
        ids[i] = i;
        // pthread_create(thread_handle, attributes, function, argument)
        pthread_create(&threads[i], NULL, compute_sum, &ids[i]);
    }

    // Wait for all 4 threads to finish before continuing
    for (int i = 0; i < THREADS; i++) {
        pthread_join(threads[i], NULL);
    }

    // Add up all partial sums
    long total = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < THREADS; i++) {
        total += partial_sum[i];
    }

    printf("\nTotal Sum = %ld\n", total);
    printf("Expected  = 5050 (sum of 1 to 100)\n");

    return 0;
}
```

**Explanation:**

| Part | What it does |
|------|-------------|
| `pthread_t threads[4]` | Stores OS-assigned thread identifiers |
| `ids[i] = i` | We create our own ID array because `&i` in a loop would be dangerous (loop changes i) |
| `pthread_create(&threads[i], NULL, compute_sum, &ids[i])` | Creates a thread. Runs `compute_sum`. Passes `&ids[i]` as argument |
| `(int*)arg` inside thread | Converts the `void*` back to `int*` so we can dereference it |
| `id * CHUNK` | Thread 0 starts at 0, Thread 1 at 25, Thread 2 at 50, Thread 3 at 75 |
| `partial_sum[id]` | Each thread writes to its own index — no two threads touch the same memory |
| `pthread_join` | Main thread waits for the thread to finish. Without this, main might exit early |

---

### Compile and Run:

```bash
gcc bank_sum.c -o bank_sum -lpthread
./bank_sum
```

### Output:
```
