## Q6 — Deadlock Handling (Banker's Algorithm)

### What is being asked?
3 printers, 4 scanners shared by 4 departments. Use Banker's Algorithm to find if the system is in a **safe state** (no deadlock possible).

### What is Banker's Algorithm?
Think of a bank: it won't give out loans if it can't guarantee everyone eventually gets paid. Similarly, the OS checks if all processes can eventually get the resources they need and finish. If yes → safe. If no → deadlock risk.

### Key matrices:
- **Allocation**: What each process currently holds
- **Max**: Maximum resources each process might ever need
- **Need = Max - Allocation**: What each process still needs
- **Available**: Resources not allocated to anyone right now

---

### FILE: `bankers.c`

```c
#include <stdio.h>

#define P 4   // Number of processes
#define R 2   // Number of resource types (printers, scanners)

int main() {
    // Resource types: [0]=Printers (3 total), [1]=Scanners (4 total)

    int allocation[P][R] = {
        {1, 1},   // P0 holds 1 printer, 1 scanner
        {1, 2},   // P1 holds 1 printer, 2 scanners
        {0, 1},   // P2 holds 0 printers, 1 scanner
        {1, 0}    // P3 holds 1 printer, 0 scanners
    };

    int max_need[P][R] = {
        {2, 2},   // P0 may need up to 2 printers, 2 scanners
        {2, 3},   // P1 may need up to 2 printers, 3 scanners
        {1, 2},   // P2 may need up to 1 printer, 2 scanners
        {2, 1}    // P3 may need up to 2 printers, 1 scanner
    };

    int available[R] = {0, 0};   // Will be calculated below
    // Total resources: 3 printers, 4 scanners
    int total[R] = {3, 4};

    // Calculate available = total - sum of allocations
    int used[R] = {0, 0};
    for (int i = 0; i < P; i++)
        for (int j = 0; j < R; j++)
            used[j] += allocation[i][j];
    for (int j = 0; j < R; j++)
        available[j] = total[j] - used[j];

    // Calculate Need matrix = Max - Allocation
    int need[P][R];
    for (int i = 0; i < P; i++)
        for (int j = 0; j < R; j++)
            need[i][j] = max_need[i][j] - allocation[i][j];

    printf("Available resources: Printers=%d, Scanners=%d\n\n",
           available[0], available[1]);

    printf("Need Matrix:\n");
    printf("P\tPrinters\tScanners\n");
    for (int i = 0; i < P; i++)
        printf("P%d\t%d\t\t%d\n", i, need[i][0], need[i][1]);

    // Safety Algorithm
    int finish[P];
    int safe_seq[P];
    int work[R];
    int count = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < P; i++) finish[i] = 0;  // No process finished yet
    for (int j = 0; j < R; j++) work[j] = available[j];  // Work = available

    printf("\nRunning Safety Algorithm...\n");

    while (count < P) {
        int found = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < P; i++) {
            if (finish[i] == 0) {
                // Check if this process's need can be satisfied by work
                int can_allocate = 1;
                for (int j = 0; j < R; j++) {
                    if (need[i][j] > work[j]) {
                        can_allocate = 0;
                        break;
                    }
                }

                if (can_allocate) {
                    // This process can finish — simulate it releasing resources
                    printf("P%d can execute. Adding its resources back to work.\n", i);
                    for (int j = 0; j < R; j++)
                        work[j] += allocation[i][j];
                    finish[i] = 1;
                    safe_seq[count++] = i;
                    found = 1;
                }
            }
        }

        if (!found) break;  // No process could run — deadlock!
    }

    if (count == P) {
        printf("\nSafe sequence: ");
        for (int i = 0; i < P; i++)
            printf("P%d ", safe_seq[i]);
        printf("\nSystem is in a SAFE state. No deadlock.\n");
    } else {
        printf("\nSystem is in DEADLOCK!\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
```

**Explanation of Safety Algorithm:**
1. Start with `work = available`
2. Find any unfinished process whose `need ≤ work`
3. Simulate it finishing: add its `allocation` back to `work`
4. Repeat until all processes finish → **safe**
5. If stuck (no process can run) → **deadlock**

---

### Compile and Run:
```bash
gcc bankers.c -o bankers
./bankers
```

