## Q8 — IPC Classical Problems (Producer-Consumer with Semaphores)

### What is being asked?
1 baker (producer) puts items on a shelf (max 5). 3 customers (consumers) take items. Use semaphores to avoid race conditions — no item consumed twice.

### What are Semaphores?
A semaphore is a counter used for signaling between threads.
- `sem_wait(s)` → Decrement. If 0, block (wait).
- `sem_post(s)` → Increment. Wake up any waiting thread.

Three semaphores needed:
- `empty` → How many empty slots on shelf (starts at 5)
- `full` → How many items on shelf (starts at 0)
- `mutex` → Ensures only one thread accesses shelf at a time

---

### FILE: `producer_consumer.c`

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <pthread.h>
#include <semaphore.h>
#include <unistd.h>

#define SHELF_SIZE  5    // Max items on shelf
#define ITEMS_MADE  9    // Total items baker will produce (3 per consumer)

int shelf[SHELF_SIZE];   // The shared shelf (circular buffer)
int in  = 0;             // Producer puts item here
int out = 0;             // Consumer takes item from here
int item_count = 0;      // Tracks item IDs

sem_t empty;   // Counts empty slots
sem_t full;    // Counts filled slots
sem_t mutex;   // Binary semaphore for mutual exclusion

// Baker (Producer) — runs in its own thread
void* baker(void* arg) {
    for (int i = 0; i < ITEMS_MADE; i++) {
        int item = i + 1;  // Item number

        sem_wait(&empty);   // Wait if shelf is full
        sem_wait(&mutex);   // Lock shelf access

        shelf[in] = item;
        printf("Baker produced item %d at slot %d\n", item, in);
        in = (in + 1) % SHELF_SIZE;  // Circular increment

        sem_post(&mutex);   // Unlock
        sem_post(&full);    // Signal: one more item available

        sleep(1);  // Baker takes time to bake
    }
    return NULL;
}

// Customer (Consumer) — each customer runs in its own thread
void* customer(void* arg) {
    int id = *((int*)arg);

    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {  // Each customer buys 3 items
        sem_wait(&full);    // Wait if shelf is empty
        sem_wait(&mutex);   // Lock shelf access

        int item = shelf[out];
        printf("Customer %d consumed item %d from slot %d\n", id, item, out);
        out = (out + 1) % SHELF_SIZE;  // Circular increment

        sem_post(&mutex);   // Unlock
        sem_post(&empty);   // Signal: one more empty slot

        sleep(2);  // Customer takes time to consume
    }
    return NULL;
}

int main() {
    pthread_t baker_thread, c1, c2, c3;
    int ids[3] = {1, 2, 3};

    // Initialize semaphores
    sem_init(&empty, 0, SHELF_SIZE);  // 5 empty slots initially
    sem_init(&full,  0, 0);           // 0 items initially
    sem_init(&mutex, 0, 1);           // Binary mutex (1 = unlocked)

    // Create threads
    pthread_create(&baker_thread, NULL, baker, NULL);
    pthread_create(&c1, NULL, customer, &ids[0]);
    pthread_create(&c2, NULL, customer, &ids[1]);
    pthread_create(&c3, NULL, customer, &ids[2]);

    // Wait for all to finish
    pthread_join(baker_thread, NULL);
    pthread_join(c1, NULL);
    pthread_join(c2, NULL);
    pthread_join(c3, NULL);

    // Cleanup
    sem_destroy(&empty);
    sem_destroy(&full);
    sem_destroy(&mutex);

    printf("\nAll items produced and consumed successfully!\n");
    return 0;
}
```

**Explanation:**

| Part | What it does |
|------|-------------|
| `sem_wait(&empty)` | Producer checks: is there space? If `empty=0`, it blocks |
| `sem_wait(&mutex)` | Producer locks the shelf before touching it |
| `shelf[in] = item; in = (in+1)%5` | Puts item in circular buffer at position `in` |
| `sem_post(&mutex)` | Unlocks shelf |
| `sem_post(&full)` | Tells consumers: one more item is ready |
| Consumer does same in reverse | Waits for `full`, locks, takes item, unlocks, posts `empty` |
| Circular buffer `%5` | When index reaches 5, it wraps back to 0 |

